Selaginella

is the sole genus in the spike moss family (
Selaginellaceae
), containing approximately 700 species that are spread over temperate, tropical, arctic, and desert regions (

). In the Flora of 
China
, 66 
Selaginella species
were recorded, most of them were used as traditional medicine (

). 

Selaginella delicatula
(Desv.) Alston

is an herb that belonging to the genus 

Selaginella

, which mainly distributed in the south of the Yangtze River. In 
China
, the whole plants are used as a folk medicine for promoting blood circulation, regulating menstruation, and heat-clearing and detoxifying (

). Previous phytochemical studies of 

S. delicatula

have led to the isolation of bioflavonoids, sterols, anthraquinones, alkaloid, neolignans and adenine analogues (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). Some of them exhibited various biological activities, such as cytotoxicity, anticancer and neuroprotection (

; 

; Chandran et al., 2013). The unusual genetic characteristics of 

Selaginella

and its evolution process suggested that plants of 

Selaginella

have the potential to synthesize unique and biologically active secondary metabolites (

; 

). As part of our continuing efforts to search for structurally unique and biologically interesting secondary metabolites from plants of the family 
Selaginellaceae
(

; 

; 

,b; 

; 

; 

), seven undescribed C 
27
steroidal glycosides were isolated from the 
n
-BuOH portion of the extract of 

S. delicatula
, Seladelicatulasine

A-G (1–7), including six cholestanol glycosides (1–6) and one spirostanol glycoside (7). The structures of 1–7 were determined by analysis of extensive spectroscopic data and enzymatic hydrolysis. Compound 6 represent the first example of 5,6-secosteroid isolated from the genus 

Selaginella

. Herein, we describe the isolation, structure elucidation, and the inhibitory activities against cholinesterase and monoamine oxidase of the steroidal glycosides.

Seladelicatulasine A (1) was obtained as an amorphous powder, whose molecular formula was determined to be C 49 H 78 O 21 based on the sodium adduct ion at m/z 1025.4891 [M + Na] + in the HRESIMS (calcd for 1025.4928). The 1D NMR spectra of 1 showed the characteristic signals for the aglycone of C 27 steroidal glycosides ascribable to two angular methyl singlets at δ H 0.98 ( CH 3 -19) and 0.75 ( CH 3 -18), two secondary methyl groups at δ H 0.96 ( CH 3 -21) and 0.83 ( CH 3 -27), seven methines including one oxygenated one [ δ C 78.5 (C-3), δ C 30.8 (C-8), δ C 49.7 (C-9), δ C 50.7 (C-14), δ C 65.8 (C-17), δ C 43.2 (C-20), δ C 35.4 (C-25)], 10 methylenes including one oxygenated carbon [ δ C 37.0 (C-1), δ C 29.5 (C-2), δ C 38.2 (C-4), δ C 31.6 (C-7), δ C 20.6 (C-11), δ C 38.4 (C-12), δ C 37.3 (C-15), δ C 39.4 (C-23), δ C 27.1 (C-24), δ C 66.5 (C-26)], a trisubstituted olefin bond carbons at δ C 121.5 (C-6) and 140.9 (C-5), two ketone carbons at δ C 218.0 (C-16) and 213.2 (C-22), and two quaternary carbons. Analysis of the 1D/2D NMR data suggested that the aglycone moiety was (25 R )-cholest-5(6)-en-3 β ,26-diol-16,22-dione (kryptogenin) (
), which was further confirmed by the 1 H– 1 H COSY and HMBC correlations ( Fig. 2 ). The configuration of C-25 was deduced to be R by the typical chemical shifts of the geminal protons at H 2 -26 ( δ a – δ b = 0.05 ppm < 0.48 ppm) (
). In addition to the aforementioned signals of the aglyconee moiety, the 1 H-NMR spectrum exhibited four anomeric protons signals at δ H 5.20 (1H, brs), 4.46 (1H, d, J = 7.8), 4.29 (1H, d, J = 7.6), 4.24 (1H, d, J = 7.7) indicated the presence of four sugar units. Enzymatic hydrolysis of 1 with cellulase afforded D-glucose, L-rhamnose and L-arabinose, whose absolute configurations were determined by GC-MS analysis (see the Supporting Information). The linkages of the sugar moiety were determined by HMBC spectrum. The HMBC correlations between δ H 4.46 (H 1 -Glu) and δ C 75.8 (C-3) suggested that the glucose was located at C-3 of the aglycone moiety, and the linkages of α -L-ara-(1 → 2)-[ α -L-rha-(1 → 3)]- α -L-ara-(1 → 4)- β -D-glc were deduced from the HMBC correlations ( Fig. 2 ) between H 1 -Rha ( δ H 5.20) and C 3 -Glc ( δ C 76.7), between H 1 -Ara-II ( δ H 4.29) and C 2 -Rha ( δ C 81.1), and between H 1 -Ara -I ( δ H 4.24) and C 4 -Glc ( δ C 79.9). Thus, the structure of 1 was determined to be (25 R )-3 β ,26-diol-cholest-5(6)-en-16,22-dione-3- O -α -L-arabinopyranosyl-(1 → 2)- α -L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1 → 3)-[ α -L-arabinopyranosyl-(1 → 4)]- β -D-glucopyranoside, and named as Seladelicatulasine A ( Fig. 1 ).

