Seladelicatulasine F (6) was isolated as a pale brown amorphous powder with molecular formula of C 33 H 56 O 8 according to the sodium adduct ion peak at m/z 603.3871 [M + Na] + (calcd for 603.3867) in the positive HRESIMS, indicating six indices of hydrogen deficiency. The 1D NMR data of 6 showed signals ascribable to five methyls, 12 methylenes including two oxygenated one, 12 methines, four quaternary carbons, including an olefin bond, a ketones carbonyl, and a β -glucopyranosyl unit, accounting for three of six degrees of unsaturation, which indicated the presence of three rings in 6. The NMR data analysis indicated that 6 was a 5,6-secosteroid glucoside. Moreover, the 1 H and 13 C NMR data of 6 were similar to those of 5-oxo-5,6-seco-3-cholesten-6-oic acid (
;
), except for the carboxyl group at C-7 was replaced by a hydroxymethyl group, and the hydrogen atom at C-25 was replaced by a β -glucopyranosyl. This was further confirmed by the HMBC correlations of H 1 -Glc ( δ H 4.24) with C-25 ( δ c 76.9) and the 1 H– 1 H COSY ( Fig. 3 ) correlations of H-6/H-7 and H-7/H-8. The relative configuration of 6 was determined to be 8 S , 9 S , 10 R , 13 R , 14 S , 17 R , 20 R by the NOESY ( Fig. 3 ) cross peaks between H-9/H-14/H-17/Me-21 and Me-18/H-8/Me-19. Enzymatic hydrolysis and GC-MS analysis of 6 allowed the characterization of a β -D-glucopyranosyl unit. Therefore, the structure of 6 was elucidated as (17 α , 20 β ) 5-oxo-5,6-seco-3-cholesten-6-ol-25-O- β -D-glucopyranoside and named as Seladelicatulasine F ( Fig. 1 ).

Seladelicatulasine G (7) was obtained as a white amorphous powder with the molecular formula C 45 H 72 O 18 , deduced from its HRESIMS ( m/z 923.4581 [M + Na] + , calcd for 923.4611) data. The 1 H NMR spectrum of 7 displayed three anomeric protons at δ H 5.13 (brs), 4.44 (d, J = 7.9), and 4.28 (d, J = 7.8), two angular methyl signals at δ H 0.79 (3H, s, CH 3 - 18), 0.97 (3H, s, CH 3 -19) and two secondary methyl signals at δ H 0.75 (3H, d, J = 6.3, CH 3 -27), 0.86 (3H, d, J = 6.9, CH 3 -21), which are the characteristic signals of a typical steroidal triglucoside (
). The 13 C NMR data of 7 revealed 45 resonances. In addition to the carbon signals of three sugar moieties, the remaining 27 signals were attributed to one ketal, one oxygenated methylenes, three oxygenated methines, a trisubstituted olefin bond, eight methylenes, six methines, four methyls, and two quaternary carbons. Detailed analysis of the NMR data, suggesting the aglycone of 7 to be a 3,23-dihydroxyspirost-5-ene derivative (
). The R configuration of C-25 was confirmed by the difference of chemical shifts of the geminal protons at H 2 -26 ( δ a – δ b = 0.20 ppm < 0.48 ppm). Moreover, the key NOESY correlations ( Fig. 3 ) of H-23/H-20, H-23/H-25, H-26 eq /H-25, H-26 ax /H-27, and H-26 ax /H-16 revealed the absolute configurations of C-20, C-22, and C-23 were S , R , S , respectively.

Optical rotations were measured on an INESA SGW-3 polarimeter (SGW, 
Shanghai
, 
China
). 1D and 2D NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker AV-400 spectrometer and a Bruker AV-500 spectrometer (Bruker, Karlsruhe, 
Germany
). HRESIMS were recorded on a Finnigan LTQ-FT (Thermo Finnigan, MA, 
USA
) and a Q-TOF mass spectrometer (Agilent 6540, CA, 
USA
). Semi-preparative or analytical HPLC was performed on an Agilent 1200 unit equipped with a DAD detector, and a siligreen C18 column (10 μm, 250 × 
10 mm
, siligreen, 
Beijing
, 
China
). GC-MS analysis of the derivative sugars were performed on a Shimadzu GCMS-QP2010 Ultra (Shimadzu, 
Japan
) using a Gas Chromatograph (GC-2010 Plus, Shimadzu, 
Japan
) equipped with a Single Quadrupole Mass Spectrometer as detector. All solvents were analytical grade. Macroporous resin HPD-100 (
Hebei
, 
China
) and Toyopearl HW-40C (TOYOPEARL, TOSOH, 
Japan
) were used for column chromatography (CC). Standard sugars (D-glucose, L-arabinose, and L-rhamnose) for GC-MS analysis were purchased from Shanghai Yuanye Biological Co. and L-Cysteine Methyl Ester Hydrochloride and N-(Trimethylsilyl) imidazole were purchased from Aladdin Industrial Co.

AChE and BChE activities were determined based on modified Ellman’ s method (
;
). (S)-acetylthiocholine iodide (ATCI), (S)-butyrylthiocholine iodide (BTCI), 5, 5 ′ -dithiobis-2-nitrobenzoic acid (DTNB), electric eel AChE and horse serum BChE were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich. The assay was carried out in the 96-well microplates. Each well was filled with 158 μ L of Ellman’ s reagent (0.15 mM of 5,5 ′ -dithiobis-2-nitrobenzoic acid) in 0.1 M phosphate buffer pH 7.4), 20 μ L of a solution of the substrate [ATCI for AChE ( K m = 0.33 mM) and BTCI for BChE ( K m = 0.30 mM)], and 2 μ L of different concentrations tested compounds in DMSO. For the blank control, the corresponding volume of DMSO was used. Huperzine A and Donepezil were used as the positive control. Reactions were started by the addition of 20 μ L of electric eel AChE or horse serum BChE solution (1 IU/mL in 0.1 M phosphate buffer pH 7.4), containing human serum albumin ( 1 mg /mL). Then, the reaction incubated at 37 ◦ C for 6 min, the optical densities were measured at 412 nm by Enzymatic Calibration instrument. Data analysis was performed on GraphPad Prism 6.0 software and expressed as mean ± standard deviation.
